Furthermore, limiting car usage can lead to increased accessibility to alternative modes of transportation. The passage by Elisabeth Rosenthal mentions how some communities have embraced the concept of ""smart planning,"" which involves separating suburban life from auto use. This means that residents are able to access their daily needs by walking or using public transportation, rather than relying solely on cars. This can lead to more vibrant and connected communities, as people are able to interact with their surroundings on a more personal level.

In addition to these environmental and social benefits, limiting car usage can also have personal benefits for individuals. By relying less on cars, individuals can reduce their expenses on car ownership, such as fuel, maintenance, and parking costs. This can free up financial resources for other important needs.

