Dear Senator [Last Name],

I am writing to express my support for keeping the Electoral College as the method of choosing the President of the United States. While there are arguments for changing to a popular vote system, I believe that the Electoral College offers several benefits that outweigh its disadvantages.

Firstly, the Electoral College ensures a certainty of outcome. In the 2012 election, President Obama received 61.7 percent of the electoral vote, even though he only received 51.3 percent of the popular votes. This highlights the importance of winning the majority of electoral votes to secure the presidency. Additionally, the winner-take-all system in most states results in a landslide victory for a candidate who has even a slight plurality in a state. This system reduces the likelihood of tied electoral votes, which could lead to further disputes and complications.

Secondly, the Electoral College promotes the idea of having a president who has trans-regional appeal. No single region has enough electoral votes to elect a president, which encourages candidates to campaign throughout the nation and understand the interests and concerns of citizens from different regions. This ensures that the president represents the entire nation, rather than favoring one particular region. It also prevents candidates with only regional appeal from becoming successful presidents.

Furthermore, the Electoral College system focuses campaign efforts on swing states. In these states, voters are more likely to pay close attention to the campaigns and make thoughtful decisions because they know their votes will decide the election. This enhances voter engagement and ensures that a more informed and thoughtful electorate determines the outcome of the election.

The Electoral College also provides a necessary balance for large states. The mal-apportionment of the Senate means that large states have less influence in the political balance. However, through the Electoral College, large states receive more attention from presidential candidates, giving their citizens a greater chance to express their political preferences.

Lastly, the Electoral College avoids the need for run-off elections. This system produces a clear winner by electing a candidate who receives a majority of the electoral votes, even if they have only a plurality of the popular votes. This reduces the complexity and uncertainty that would arise from run-off elections when no candidate wins a majority of the votes cast.

While some argue that the Electoral College may discourage potential voters in states where their preferred candidate has no chance of winning, the turnout in presidential elections suggests otherwise. About half of the eligible American population voted in the 2012 election, indicating that voters participate to express their political preferences rather than with the expectation of swinging the national election.

In conclusion, the Electoral College serves as an effective method for choosing the President of the United States. It provides certainty of outcome, ensures a president with trans-regional appeal, focuses campaign efforts on swing states, gives necessary weight to large states, and avoids the complexities of run-off elections. These advantages outweigh the potential disadvantages of the system. Therefore, I urge you to support the continuation of the Electoral College.

Thank you for considering my views on this important matter. I trust that you will make a decision that best serves the interests of our nation and its citizens.

Yours sincerely,

