Dear [State Senator's Name],

I am writing to express my opinion regarding the Electoral College and its role in the election of the President of the United States. After reviewing various texts on this topic, I firmly believe that the current system of the Electoral College should be maintained, rather than shifting to a popular vote system.

One of the main arguments in favor of the Electoral College is the certainty of outcome that it provides. In his article, ""In Defense of the Electoral College,"" Judge Richard A. Posner explains that the winner of the Electoral College almost always exceeds their share of the popular vote. This ensures a clear and definitive result, reducing the likelihood of a disputed election outcome. Additionally, the winner-take-all method in most states creates a landslide victory, preventing a tie in the nationwide electoral vote.

Another significant advantage of the Electoral College is that it necessitates a candidate to have trans-regional appeal. This means that no single region, such as the South or the Northeast, has enough electoral votes to elect a president on their own. As Judge Posner points out in his article, this prompts candidates to campaign across various regions and address the concerns of voters from different parts of the country. This inclusive approach is crucial for a successful presidency and prevents any region from feeling disenfranchised.

The Electoral College's focus on swing states also leads to increased voter attention and informed decision-making. Rather than solely targeting safe states, candidates are compelled to engage with voters in toss-up states. These states, as argued by Judge Posner, tend to have more thoughtful voters who actively engage with campaign information and listen to competing candidates. By giving these voters a decisive role in the election, the Electoral College ensures that the most thoughtful citizens have the power to choose the president.

Furthermore, the Electoral College preserves the political balance between small and large states. Due to the Constitution's mal-apportionment of the Senate, smaller states would be at a disadvantage in a purely popular vote system. By allocating electoral votes based on Congressional representation, larger states receive more attention from presidential candidates, balancing the power dynamics between states of varying sizes.

Lastly, the Electoral College avoids the need for run-off elections, which can complicate the election process. As demonstrated by examples from history provided by Judge Posner, the Electoral College consistently produces a clear winner even if a candidate does not obtain a majority of the popular vote. This reduces the pressure for run-off elections and facilitates a smoother transition of power.

Although critics argue that a popular vote system may increase voter engagement in states deemed safe for one party, we must acknowledge that voters understand that their individual vote does not swing a national election. It is the desire to express a political preference that motivates citizens to participate in the electoral process. Consequently, the Electoral College's unique approach in distributing electoral votes reflects the overall sentiments of the American people who actively participate in presidential elections.

In conclusion, based on the various readings and arguments presented, I strongly support maintaining the Electoral College system for selecting the President of the United States. Its certainty of outcome, inclusivity of trans-regional appeal, focus on swing states, balance of power between small and large states, and avoidance of run-off elections all contribute to a fair and effective electoral process. The Electoral College upholds the principles established by our founding fathers and ensures that the voices of all Americans are heard. I urge you to consider these points when discussing this matter in the legislature and to vote in favor of maintaining the Electoral College.

Thank you for your time and consideration.

Sincerely,

