"Dear [State Senator],

I am writing to express my support for keeping the Electoral College as the method for choosing the President of the United States. While there are arguments against this system, I believe that the Electoral College has several practical advantages that make it a valuable aspect of our democracy.

One of the main reasons to retain the Electoral College is the certainty of outcome that it provides. In the rare event of a dispute over the outcome of an Electoral College vote, it is less likely to occur than a dispute over the popular vote. This is because the winning candidate's share of the electoral vote usually exceeds their share of the popular vote. With the winner-take-all system in most states, even a slight plurality in a state can result in a landslide electoral-vote victory. While a tie in the nationwide electoral vote is possible, it is highly unlikely. Therefore, the Electoral College helps to ensure a clear outcome in the presidential election.

Another advantage of the Electoral College is that it necessitates a presidential candidate to have trans-regional appeal. No single region has enough electoral votes to elect a president, meaning that candidates must appeal to a broad range of voters across the country. This helps to prevent a president with only regional appeal from being elected, ensuring that the president represents the interests of the entire nation. In a country as diverse as ours, it is important for the president to be able to understand and address the needs of citizens from all regions.

The swing state phenomenon is also a benefit of the Electoral College system. Because electoral votes are awarded on a winner-take-all basis, candidates are incentivized to focus their campaign efforts on the toss-up states. This means that voters in these swing states are more likely to pay close attention to the campaign and make informed decisions. By giving greater weight to the votes of these thoughtful voters, the Electoral College allows for a more informed electorate to have a greater say in the election.

In addition, the Electoral College helps to balance the power between large and small states. The mal-apportionment of the Senate in the Constitution gives smaller states more influence in the Electoral College. This is beneficial because it prevents presidential candidates from solely focusing on heavily populated states, as they would in a popular vote system. By giving smaller states more attention, the Electoral College ensures that the concerns of citizens in these states are not overshadowed by those in larger states.

Finally, the Electoral College avoids the need for run-off elections. In cases where no candidate receives a majority of the votes cast, as seen in 1968 and 1992, the Electoral College still produces a clear winner. This eliminates the need for further run-off elections, which could complicate the presidential election process.

While the Electoral College may have its critics, it is clear that the system has practical advantages that serve our democracy well. The certainty of outcome, representation for all regions, voter attention in swing states, balance between large and small states, and prevention of run-off elections are all reasons to retain this method for choosing the President of the United States. I urge you to consider these points when making decisions about the electoral system.

Thank you for your attention to this matter.

Sincerely,
