"Dear [State Senator],

I am writing to express my strong support for keeping the Electoral College as the method of choosing the President of the United States. While there are arguments for changing to an election by popular vote, I believe that the Electoral College provides important benefits that outweigh any potential drawbacks.

One of the main reasons to retain the Electoral College is the certainty of outcome that it provides. In the Electoral College system, the winning candidate’s share of the Electoral College usually exceeds their share of the popular vote. This reduces the likelihood of disputes over the election outcome, as we saw in the 2000 election. Additionally, the winner-take-all method of awarding electoral votes ensures that even a slight plurality in a state results in a landslide victory in terms of electoral votes. This system prevents a tie in the nationwide electoral vote, which would create uncertainty and potentially lead to further disputes.

Another advantage of the Electoral College is that it ensures that the President has trans-regional appeal. No single region of the country has enough electoral votes to elect a President, which means that candidates must appeal to voters across the nation. This fosters a sense of inclusivity and ensures that the President represents the interests of all regions. In contrast, a direct popular vote system could result in candidates focusing solely on heavily populated areas, neglecting the concerns of less populated regions.

The Electoral College also encourages candidates to focus their campaign efforts on swing states. This means that voters in these states receive more attention and information from the candidates, making them more informed and thoughtful voters. By giving swing states more influence in the election process, the Electoral College ensures that the most important and contested issues receive the necessary attention and consideration.

Furthermore, the Electoral College balances out the political influence of big states versus small states. The winner-take-all method of awarding electoral votes means that even a close popular vote in a large state results in a significant number of electoral votes for the winning candidate. This gives large states more weight in the political balance and prevents smaller states from being overshadowed.

Lastly, the Electoral College avoids the need for runoff elections. If no candidate receives a majority of the popular votes, runoff elections can become complex and time-consuming. The Electoral College system consistently produces a clear winner, eliminating the need for additional elections and ensuring a smooth transition of power.

While critics argue that the Electoral College may discourage potential voters in states where their preferred candidate has no chance of winning, it is important to note that voter turnout in presidential elections remains high. Voters are motivated by the desire to express their political preference, rather than the belief that their single vote will determine the outcome.

In conclusion, the Electoral College provides certainty of outcome, ensures trans-regional appeal, focuses attention on swing states, balances political influence, and avoids the need for runoff elections. These benefits outweigh any potential drawbacks and make a strong case for retaining the Electoral College. I urge you to support the continuation of this important system in our presidential elections.

Thank you for your attention to this matter.

Sincerely,
