One of the main advantages of the Electoral College is the certainty of outcome that it provides. In a dispute over the outcome of the Electoral College vote, it is less likely to occur compared to a dispute over the popular vote, as the winning candidate's share of the Electoral College usually exceeds their share of the popular vote. This ensures a clear winner and reduces the likelihood of prolonged uncertainty and potential unrest.

