Subject: Why We Should Retain the Electoral College in Presidential Elections

Dear Senator [Last Name],

I hope this letter finds you well. I am writing to express my support for retaining the Electoral College in the election of the President of the United States. While some argue for a shift towards a popular vote system, I believe it is imperative to consider the practical reasons outlined by Judge Richard A. Posner in his article, ""In Defense of the Electoral College,"" as well as other relevant information on the electoral process.

Firstly, the Electoral College system provides certainty in electoral outcomes. Although disputes may arise, as in the 2000 election between Gore and Bush, they are less likely with the Electoral College than with a direct popular vote. This is because the winner's share of the Electoral College vote typically exceeds their share of the popular vote. For instance, President Obama received 61.7% of the electoral vote in 2012, even though he secured only 51.3% of the popular votes cast for him and Romney. Each state's winner-take-all approach ensures a clear victor in that state, minimizing the likelihood of a nationwide tie or contentious result.

Secondly, the Electoral College promotes national representation. By requiring presidential candidates to have trans-regional appeal, it prevents candidates from solely focusing on specific regions and neglecting the interests of others. To win the presidency, a candidate must secure electoral votes from various states across the country. This reduces the risk of a president with only regional appeal, who may disregard the needs and concerns of other regions. The residents of each region can feel assured that their vote and interests are being represented at the national level.

Thirdly, the Electoral College system encourages candidates to campaign in swing states. These are the states that could potentially shift the outcome of the election, leading candidates to invest time and resources in engaging with swing voters. This results in a more informed electorate, as these voters closely scrutinize competing candidates and their policy proposals. It ensures that thoughtful and engaged voters, who have received ample attention from candidates, have the greatest influence on the election's outcome.

Additionally, the electoral process grants due weight to larger states, protecting them from disproportionate influence. The mal-apportionment of the Senate in the Constitution may disadvantage large states, but the Electoral College system mitigates this by granting them additional attention from presidential candidates. In 2012, Florida's close popular vote translated into 29 electoral votes, while a similarly small margin in Wyoming yielded only 3 electoral votes. The Electoral College system thus allows for a balance where larger states receive proportionate representation in presidential campaigns.

Lastly, the Electoral College avoids the complications of run-off elections. In cases when no candidate secures a majority of the popular vote, pressure may arise for run-off elections, which would further complicate the electoral process. By invariably producing a clear winner, the Electoral College system provides stability and efficiency.

Although critics argue that the Electoral College may discourage potential voters if they believe their vote holds little weight in non-competitive states, it is worth noting that voter turnout remains significant. In the 2012 elections, despite no voter's vote swinging a national election, approximately half of eligible Americans exercised their democratic right. Voters participate to express their political preferences, even if they understand the unlikely chance of their single vote deciding the outcome.

In conclusion, the Electoral College system is vital for ensuring certainty, national representation, swing state importance, attention to larger states, and avoiding run-off elections. I believe these practical reasons outweigh the arguments for a shift towards a direct popular vote in the election of the President of the United States. I kindly request that in your capacity as our state senator, you consider retaining the Electoral College system and support efforts to protect this time-honored democratic process.

Thank you for your attention and consideration. I trust that you will make an informed decision on this matter, keeping the best interests of your constituents and our nation in mind.

Sincerely,

