Dear Senator [Senator's Last Name],

I am writing to express my views on the Electoral College and to argue in favor of keeping this system for electing the President of the United States. I believe that the Electoral College provides several important benefits that should be considered before any decision is made to change to a popular vote system. I have drawn upon information from various sources to support my argument.

Firstly, the Electoral College system ensures certainty of outcome in presidential elections. Although disputes can arise, such as the case in 2000, these instances are rare and less likely to occur than disputes over the popular vote. This is because the winner of the electoral vote usually exceeds their share of the popular vote. For instance, in the 2012 election, President Obama received 61.7% of the electoral vote compared to only 51.3% of the popular vote. This system allows for a clear winner and reduces uncertainty in the outcome.

Secondly, the Electoral College fosters the idea of having a president who appeals to all regions of the country. Since no single region has enough electoral votes to elect a president, candidates must have trans-regional appeal to garner support from different parts of the country. This prevents a candidate with only regional appeal from becoming president and ensures that all regions feel represented by the elected president. This is crucial for maintaining national unity.

Another benefit of the Electoral College is its focus on swing states. The winner-take-all method encourages candidates to direct their campaign efforts towards these states, where the election is usually decided. Voters in swing states pay close attention to the campaign and carefully consider the competing candidates, ensuring that the most thoughtful voters have a significant say in the election. This leads to a more informed electorate and a more representative outcome.

Furthermore, the Electoral College restores balance for larger states. While the Senate apportionment may disadvantage larger states, the Electoral College gives these states more attention during campaigns. For example, in the 2012 election, the popular vote was close in Florida, and President Obama won the state, earning 29 electoral votes. In comparison, a victory by the same margin in Wyoming would only yield 3 electoral votes. This balance allows for fair representation of both large and small states in the election process.

Finally, the Electoral College eliminates the need for run-off elections. Should no candidate receive a majority of the votes cast, the Electoral College still produces a clear winner. This avoids the complexity and additional costs associated with run-off elections and ensures a swift and decisive outcome for the presidency.

I understand that there are arguments against the Electoral College, such as concerns about the disenfranchisement of voters in states where they have little chance of influencing the outcome. However, it is important to note that voter turnout in presidential elections is already motivated by expressing a political preference rather than the belief that a single vote will decide the election. In the 2012 election, despite this reality, approximately half of the eligible American population still voted.

In conclusion, the Electoral College has several advantages that should be taken into account before deciding to change to a popular vote system. It ensures certainty of outcome, promotes a president with trans-regional appeal, focuses campaign efforts on swing states, restores balance for larger states, and avoids the need for run-off elections. These benefits contribute to a more representative and unified democracy in the United States. Therefore, I urge you to support the continuation of the Electoral College system.

Thank you for considering my views on this matter. I trust that you will carefully evaluate the information provided from the various sources and make the best decision in the best interest of our nation.

Sincerely,

