Dear [State Senator's Name],

I am writing to express my support for the Electoral College system in selecting the President of the United States. While many argue for a switch to election by popular vote, I believe that the Electoral College is a vital component of our democratic process that should be preserved. I would like to present you with five reasons, derived from various sources, as to why we should keep the Electoral College.

Firstly, the Electoral College provides certainty of outcome. There have been very few instances in history where the winner of the electoral vote has differed from the winner of the popular vote. This means that the Electoral College system is generally reliable in ensuring that the presidency is given to the candidate who receives the majority of electoral votes.

Secondly, the Electoral College ensures that the president is not just a regional favorite, but someone with trans-regional appeal. Candidates must have support and appeal across various regions in order to secure the necessary electoral votes. This prevents candidates from focusing solely on populous regions and leaving others neglected. It ensures that the president represents the interests of all regions and not just those of a few.

Thirdly, the winner-take-all method of awarding electoral votes encourages candidates to pay attention to swing states, or toss-up states. This leads to campaigns that engage the most thoughtful voters, who are more likely to carefully consider each candidate's platform and make an informed decision. By focusing on these states, candidates are able to directly address the concerns and needs of a diverse group of voters.

Fourthly, the Electoral College provides a balance of power to larger states. Due to the mal-apportionment of the Senate, larger states lose some weight in the political balance. However, through the Electoral College, large states receive more attention from presidential candidates than smaller states. This ensures that the concerns and issues of large states are not overshadowed by the interests of smaller states.

Lastly, the Electoral College avoids the need for run-off elections. In instances where no candidate receives a majority of the popular vote, a run-off election would be required. This would significantly complicate the election process. The Electoral College, on the other hand, consistently produces a clear winner, eliminating the need for subsequent elections and potential confusion.

It can be argued that the Electoral College may discourage voters in states where their preferred candidate has no hope of winning. However, even in such cases, approximately half of the eligible American population still participates in presidential elections. Voters are motivated by their desire to express a political preference rather than the belief that their single vote will determine the outcome.

In conclusion, the Electoral College remains a crucial part of our democratic process. It ensures certainty in outcomes, promotes trans-regional appeal, focuses campaigns on swing states, balances power for larger states, and avoids the need for run-off elections. While there are arguments in favor of a popular vote system, I believe that the benefits provided by the Electoral College outweighs the perceived disadvantages.

I respectfully urge you to consider and support the preservation of the Electoral College system. Thank you for your attention to this matter.

Sincerely,

