Limiting car usage can also have economic advantages. In the German suburb of Vauban, where cars are not allowed, 70 percent of families do not own cars, and 57 percent of residents sold their cars to move there. This has resulted in reduced expenses on car ownership and maintenance, allowing families to allocate their resources towards other needs. Additionally, car-free initiatives, such as the car-free day in Bogota, promote alternative modes of transportation like buses, bikes, and walking. These alternatives are often more cost-effective and can help individuals save money on fuel, parking, and maintenance costs.

