Subject: The Importance of Preserving the Electoral College

Dear Senator [Senator's Last Name],

I am writing to express my support for keeping the Electoral College as our method for electing the President of the United States. While there are arguments in favor of changing to a popular vote system, I believe that the Electoral College provides several crucial benefits that should not be overlooked. This view is informed by the information provided in three different sources, including ""What Is the Electoral College?"" by the Office of the Federal Register, ""The Indefensible Electoral College: Why even the best-laid defenses of the system are wrong"" by Bradford Plumer, and ""In Defense of the Electoral College: Five reasons to keep our despised method of choosing the President"" by Judge Richard A. Posner.

Contrary to the belief that the Electoral College is undemocratic, it serves the valuable purpose of ensuring certainty of outcome. While a dispute over the outcome of an Electoral College vote is possible, it is less likely than a dispute over the popular vote. The winning candidate's share of the Electoral College consistently exceeds their share of the popular vote. In addition, the winner-take-all method of awarding electoral votes prevents a tie in the nationwide electoral vote, which is highly unlikely due to the even number of total votes. This certainty of outcome is crucial for maintaining stability and preventing prolonged election disputes.

Furthermore, the Electoral College fosters a sense of inclusiveness by requiring presidential candidates to have trans-regional appeal. In our diverse nation, no single region has enough electoral votes to elect a President. Candidates with only regional appeal are unlikely to be successful, as residents of other regions may feel disenfranchised. The Electoral College encourages candidates to campaign across various regions, thus ensuring that the President represents the interests of the entire nation.

Moreover, the Electoral College's winner-take-all system and focus on swing states have their advantages. By concentrating campaign efforts on toss-up states, candidates pay more attention to voters who are likely to make thoughtful decisions. This engagement leads to the most thoughtful voters deciding the election, ensuring that the President is chosen by a well-informed electorate. Additionally, the Electoral College restores some political balance for large states, compensating for the mal-apportionment of the Senate. This attention to both swing states and large states ensures that the President is accountable to a diverse range of voters.

Finally, the Electoral College avoids the need for run-off elections, which can complicate the electoral process. By invariably producing a clear winner, it eliminates the pressure for run-off elections when no candidate receives a majority of the votes cast. This streamlined process ensures a decisive outcome while also reducing costs and logistical challenges associated with run-off elections.

In conclusion, the Electoral College plays a crucial role in our democratic system and should be preserved. Its ability to ensure certainty of outcome, foster inclusiveness and trans-regional appeal, focus on swing states, provide political weight to large states, and avoid run-off elections outweigh the arguments in favor of changing to a popular vote system. While it is important to continually evaluate our election processes, the Electoral College has proven its value over time and should be maintained.

I encourage you to consider these points and advocate for the preservation of the Electoral College in order to uphold the principles that our founding fathers intended.

Thank you for your attention to this matter.

Sincerely,

