Limiting car usage can also lead to more sustainable and livable communities. The passage about the German suburb, Vauban, highlights the concept of ""smart planning"" where suburbs are separated from auto use. In this community, car ownership is allowed but limited parking spaces are available. As a result, a significant percentage of families do not own cars and the streets are car-free. This promotes a safer and more pedestrian-friendly environment, with less noise and pollution from cars. Stores are placed within walking distance, making it more convenient for residents to access daily necessities without relying on cars.

