Subject: The Importance of Keeping the Electoral College

Dear Senator [Senator's Last Name],

I am writing to express my support for the Electoral College and to urge you to continue advocating for its preservation. While some argue for a shift towards a popular vote system, I am convinced that maintaining the Electoral College is crucial for the integrity and effectiveness of our presidential elections.

First and foremost, the Electoral College ensures certainty of outcome. In the event of a dispute, the winning candidate's share of the Electoral College will almost always exceed their share of the popular vote. This prevents extended legal battles, as witnessed in the 2000 election, and allows for a smooth and decisive outcome. With President Obama's 2012 election, he received 61.7% of the electoral vote, while only winning 51.3% of the popular vote. This discrepancy provides a clear indication of the stability the Electoral College brings to our elections.

Furthermore, the Electoral College promotes a sense of unity by requiring presidential candidates to have trans-regional appeal. No single region possesses enough electoral votes to secure the presidency. As a result, candidates are incentivized to campaign across the nation, connecting with voters in various states. This approach ensures that the elected president truly represents the interests of all Americans and prevents candidates from focusing solely on a specific region while neglecting others.

The winner-take-all method employed by the Electoral College also benefits swing states. By focusing campaign efforts on states where the outcomes are uncertain, candidates are compelled to engage with voters, listen to their concerns, and provide persuasive arguments. This heightened attention fosters thoughtful voting, creating a more informed electorate and increasing voter participation.

Additionally, the Electoral College balances the influence of large and small states. The malapportionment of the Senate, as outlined in the Constitution, can be mitigated through the weighting of electoral votes. For example, in 2012, though the popular vote in Florida was close, President Obama received 29 electoral votes, compared to winning Wyoming where the winner would have received only 3. This means that candidates are motivated to campaign in larger states, providing an opportunity for these states to have their concerns and issues addressed.

Finally, the Electoral College eliminates the need for run-off elections. It ensures that the winner always obtains a majority of the electoral votes, averting the complications that arise in the absence of a clear majority winner. Run-off elections would add complexity to the presidential election process and might even discourage voter participation. The Electoral College, with its clear winner, maintains the simplicity and efficiency of our elections.

I understand that some argue in favor of a popular vote system. However, relying on one source of information can be problematic. Taking into account the information presented in ""What Is the Electoral College?"" and ""The Indefensible Electoral College,"" it becomes clear that the Electoral College has a strong foundation in the Constitution and provides superior benefits.

In conclusion, I urge you to consider the value and merits of the Electoral College system. It contributes to the stability, unity, and fairness of our presidential elections, ensuring that the voices of all Americans are represented. I believe that preserving the Electoral College is vital for upholding the integrity of our democracy.

Thank you for your time and consideration. I trust that you will prioritize the preservation of the Electoral College and continue supporting this important institution.

Sincerely,

