"Dear [State Senator],

I am writing to you today to express my support for the Electoral College system and urge you to consider the practical reasons for keeping this method of choosing the president of the United States. Though it may not be a perfect system, it has several advantages that should not be overlooked.

First and foremost, the Electoral College provides certainty in determining the outcome of the presidential election. While disputes over the outcome can still occur, they are less likely compared to a popular vote system. This is because the winner of the Electoral College usually receives a larger share of the electoral votes than their share of the popular vote. This prevents the possibility of a close popular vote leading to ongoing disputes and potential chaos.

Another important advantage of the Electoral College is that it ensures that the president has trans-regional appeal and support. No single region of the country has enough electoral votes to elect a president on its own, forcing candidates to campaign and appeal to a wider range of voters across different states. This helps to prevent a candidate with only regional appeal from becoming president and ensures that the president represents the interests of diverse regions and populations.

Additionally, the winner-take-all method of awarding electoral votes encourages candidates to focus their campaign efforts on swing states. This means that voters in these states are more likely to pay close attention to the campaign, carefully considering the candidates and issues at hand. These swing state voters tend to be the most thoughtful and informed, and they should be the ones who have the most influence in deciding the outcome of the election.

Furthermore, the Electoral College system restores some balance and attention to large states. Due to the mal-apportionment of the Senate, large states tend to have less influence in the political process. However, the Electoral College ensures that large states receive more attention from presidential candidates because winning a large state translates to a higher number of electoral votes. This gives large states a greater say in determining the outcome of the election.

Lastly, the Electoral College eliminates the need for run-off elections. It guarantees that the winner of the election has a clear majority of the electoral votes, even if they only have a plurality of the popular vote. This avoids the complications and uncertainties that arise from multiple rounds of voting and ensures a decisive outcome.

While opponents argue that the Electoral College may discourage potential voters in states dominated by one party, it is important to note that a majority of eligible voters still participate in presidential elections. Furthermore, voters are motivated by their desire to express their political preferences rather than the belief that their single vote will decide the election.

In conclusion, the Electoral College system is not without its flaws, but it provides necessary certainty, ensures trans-regional appeal, focuses campaigns on swing states, gives large states more influence, and avoids the complications of run-off elections. For these practical reasons, I believe it is important to keep the Electoral College or at least carefully consider any proposed changes. Thank you for your attention to this matter.

