One of the main reasons to retain the Electoral College is the certainty of outcome that it provides. In most cases, the winning candidate's share of the electoral vote exceeds their share of the popular vote, ensuring a clear winner. This helps to prevent disputes over the election outcome and provides stability to the process. While there have been a few instances where the winner of the popular vote did not win the presidency, these cases are rare and do not outweigh the benefits of the Electoral College.

Another advantage of the Electoral College is that it ensures that the president has trans-regional appeal. Because no single region has enough electoral votes to elect a president, candidates must appeal to a broad range of voters across the country. This helps to prevent a candidate with only regional appeal from being elected and ensures that the president represents the interests of all Americans, not just one region.

