Subject: Keeping the Electoral College for Presidential Elections

Dear Senator [Senator's Last Name],

I am writing to express my support for keeping the Electoral College for the election of the President of the United States. While there have been calls to change to a system of election by popular vote, I believe that the Electoral College is an integral and important part of our democratic process for several reasons.

Firstly, the Electoral College provides certainty of outcome. As Judge Richard A. Posner aptly points out, the winner of the Electoral College invariably receives a greater share of electoral votes than their share of the popular vote. This ensures that a winning candidate has a clear and indisputable mandate to govern. A dispute over the outcome of the popular vote is more likely to occur and is fraught with greater uncertainty.

Secondly, the Electoral College ensures that the President represents all regions of the country. No single region has enough electoral votes to elect a President, which means that candidates have to appeal to a diverse set of voters across the nation. This prevents a candidate with only regional appeal from becoming president and ensures that the interests of all regions are taken into account.

Thirdly, the winner-take-all method of awarding electoral votes encourages candidates to campaign in swing states. This means that voters in those states have a greater say in deciding the election. It allows for a more informed and thoughtful electorate, as those voters are more likely to pay attention to the campaign and closely scrutinize the candidates' policies and positions. This ensures that the election is decided by the most engaged and informed citizens.

Furthermore, the Electoral College helps to balance political power between large and small states. As illustrated by Posner, a victory by a small margin in a large state like Florida can yield significant electoral votes, while the same victory in a small state like Wyoming would only provide a few. This prevents larger states from having an overwhelming influence on the outcome of the election and ensures that candidates pay attention to the concerns and interests of voters in smaller states.

Finally, the Electoral College avoids the need for costly and complicated runoff elections. By consistently producing a clear winner, it eliminates the pressure for further rounds of voting when no candidate receives a majority of the popular vote. This helps to streamline the election process and ensures a smooth transition of power.

In conclusion, the Electoral College serves as a vital component of our democratic system by providing certainty of outcome, ensuring regional representation, promoting engagement in swing states, balancing power between large and small states, and avoiding the need for runoff elections. While some argue for a change to a popular vote system, I believe that the Electoral College is a flawed, yet effective mechanism for electing the President. I urge you to consider these points and support the preservation of the Electoral College.

Thank you for your attention to this matter. I look forward to your response and appreciate your efforts to represent the interests of our great state.

Sincerely,

