Dear Senator [Last Name],

I am writing to express my support for keeping the Electoral College as the method of choosing the President of the United States. While I understand that there are arguments for changing to a popular vote system, I believe that the Electoral College provides important benefits that should be considered.

First and foremost, the Electoral College ensures certainty of outcome. This system allows for a clear winner to emerge, avoiding the possibility of a prolonged dispute over the popular vote count. This was demonstrated during the 2012 election, where President Obama received a significant share of the electoral vote compared to his share of the popular vote. The winner-take-all method used by most states in allocating electoral votes creates a landslide victory, reducing the likelihood of a tie in the nationwide electoral vote.

Additionally, the Electoral College promotes inclusivity by requiring a presidential candidate to have trans-regional appeal. No single region has enough electoral votes to elect a president, meaning that candidates must appeal to voters across the country. This prevents a candidate with only regional support from becoming president, ensuring that the interests of all regions are considered. It helps prevent the feeling of disenfranchisement among the residents of regions whose votes do not count in a popular vote system.

The Electoral College also encourages candidates to focus their campaign efforts on swing states. This ensures that voters in these states, who are likely to be the most thoughtful and informed, have a significant say in the election outcome. It fosters a sense of engagement and participation among voters in toss-up states, as they know that their votes could decide the election. It also prevents candidates from ignoring smaller states, as the winner-take-all allocation of electoral votes gives more weight to states with higher populations.

Furthermore, the Electoral College balances the weight of large and small states, addressing the mal-apportionment of the Senate outlined in the Constitution. A large state receives more attention from presidential candidates in a campaign, as their victory margin in a large state would yield more electoral votes compared to a small state. This ensures that the interests of both large and small states are taken into account during the campaign process.

Lastly, the Electoral College eliminates the need for run-off elections. In cases where no candidate receives a majority of the popular vote, a run-off election would complicate the presidential election process. The Electoral College, by design, produces a clear winner and avoids the need for further elections.

While some argue that the Electoral College may discourage voters in states where their vote has no impact, the data from the 2012 election shows that approximately half of the eligible American population participated in the election. Voters are driven by their desire to express a political preference rather than the belief that their vote will swing a national election.

In conclusion, the Electoral College provides important benefits that should be considered when discussing the method of choosing the President of the United States. It ensures certainty of outcome, promotes inclusivity, encourages engagement in swing states, balances the weight of large and small states, and eliminates the need for run-off elections. For these reasons, I urge you to support and advocate for the continuation of the Electoral College system.

Thank you for considering my perspective on this matter. I appreciate your dedication to serving our state and country.

Sincerely,

