"Dear Senator,

I am writing to express my support for keeping the Electoral College system for electing the President of the United States. While some argue that it is outdated and undemocratic, I believe that there are five practical reasons for retaining this system.

Firstly, the Electoral College provides certainty of outcome. In the rare event of a dispute over the outcome, it is less likely to occur with the Electoral College than with a popular vote system. This is because a candidate's share of the Electoral College usually exceeds their share of the popular vote. Additionally, the winner-take-all method of awarding electoral votes ensures that even a slight plurality in a state leads to a landslide electoral-vote victory in that state. This makes a tie in the nationwide electoral vote highly unlikely.

Secondly, the Electoral College ensures that the president represents all regions of the country. No region has enough electoral votes to elect a president on its own, meaning that candidates must have trans-regional appeal. This prevents a candidate with only regional favorability from becoming president, as they would be unlikely to be successful in governing and could leave residents from other regions feeling disenfranchised.

Thirdly, the Electoral College system encourages candidates to campaign extensively in swing states. These states hold the key to deciding the election and therefore receive the most attention from candidates. Voters in swing states are more likely to pay close attention to the campaign, becoming thoughtful voters who are well-informed and able to make informed decisions.

Furthermore, the Electoral College restores balance to the political weight of large states. While the mal-apportionment of the Senate gives smaller states more influence, the Electoral College ensures that large states receive more attention from presidential candidates. This balance prevents candidates from solely focusing on the most populous states and allows for more representation of diverse interests across the country.

Lastly, the Electoral College system avoids the need for run-off elections when no candidate receives a majority of the votes. This simplifies the presidential election process and produces a clear winner, reducing the pressure for additional elections.

While some argue that the popular vote system would be fairer, it is important to note that the current system encourages voter participation. Even voters who know their state is unlikely to swing in their preferred candidate's favor still turn out to express their political preference. Furthermore, the Electoral College system has only resulted in a discrepancy between the popular vote and the electoral vote on rare occasions, and the practical benefits it provides outweigh this minor criticism.

In conclusion, the Electoral College system should be retained for electing the President of the United States. Its certainty of outcome, representation of all regions, focus on swing states, balance of large and small states, and avoidance of run-off elections make it a practical and fair system. I urge you to consider these reasons and support the continuation of the Electoral College.

Thank you for your attention to this matter.

Sincerely,
