"Dear Senator,

I am writing to you today to express my support for keeping the Electoral College as the method of selecting the President of the United States. While some argue for a change to a popular vote system, I believe that the Electoral College has five practical reasons for its continuation.

Firstly, the Electoral College ensures a certainty of outcome. The winning candidate's share of the Electoral College almost always exceeds their share of the popular vote, reducing the likelihood of disputes. While it is possible for there to be a tie in the electoral vote, it is highly unlikely. The winner-take-all system used by most states also creates a landslide victory for the winning candidate.

Secondly, the Electoral College ensures that every region has a say in the election. No single region has enough electoral votes to elect a president, so candidates with only regional appeal have no incentive to heavily campaign in those states. This promotes the need for a candidate to have trans-regional appeal, ensuring that they will represent the interests of all regions and not just their own base.

Thirdly, the Electoral College promotes the importance of swing states. The winner-take-all method of awarding electoral votes encourages candidates to focus their campaign efforts on these toss-up states. This leads to more thoughtful voters who have received more information and attention from the candidates. It is these voters who should decide the outcome of the election.

Fourthly, the Electoral College restores some balance to the political power of large states. The mal-apportionment of the Senate gives large states less weight in the political balance. The Electoral College allows large states to receive more attention from presidential candidates during the campaign, creating a fairer representation of the population.

Finally, the Electoral College avoids the need for run-off elections. In cases where no candidate receives a majority of the popular votes, the Electoral College ensures that a clear winner emerges. This prevents the complication of run-off elections and provides a decisive outcome.

While some argue that the Electoral College may discourage potential voters in states where their preferred candidate has no chance of winning, it is important to note that voters in presidential elections are people who want to express their political preferences, not those who believe their single vote will decide the election.

In conclusion, the Electoral College has practical reasons for its continuation that promote fairness, trans-regional representation, and a certainty of outcome. It ensures that every region has a say and prevents run-off elections. I urge you to consider these reasons and support the Electoral College in our democratic process of electing the President of the United States.

