"Dear State Senator,

I am writing to express my opinion on the topic of whether to keep the Electoral College or change to an election by popular vote for the president of the United States. After analyzing the information from various texts, I am in favor of keeping the Electoral College system. The Electoral College has several practical reasons that support its retention.

One of the main reasons to keep the Electoral College is the certainty of outcome. While disputes over the outcome of an Electoral College vote are possible, they are less likely than disputes over the popular vote. This is because the winning candidate's share of the Electoral College usually exceeds their share of the popular vote. The winner-take-all system in most states creates a landslide electoral-vote victory if a candidate has even a slight plurality in a state. Therefore, ties in the nationwide electoral vote are highly unlikely, ensuring a clear winner.

Another reason to support the Electoral College is that it ensures that the president has trans-regional appeal. No region in the country has enough electoral votes to elect a president alone. This means that a candidate with only regional appeal, such as a solid favorite in the South, has no incentive to campaign heavily in those states. This encourages candidates to have a broader appeal and prevents them from only focusing on specific regions. It is important for a successful president to have support from all regions of the country.

The Electoral College system also benefits swing states. The winner-take-all method of awarding electoral votes incentivizes candidates to focus their campaign efforts on toss-up states. Voters in these states are more likely to pay close attention to the campaign and be thoughtful in their decision-making. They become the most critical voters in determining the outcome of the election. This ensures that the most thoughtful and engaged voters have the power to decide the presidency.

Additionally, the Electoral College balances the weight of big states in the political process. Large states with high populations already have an advantage in the House of Representatives due to their representation based on population. The Electoral College restores some of the balance by ensuring that large states also receive more attention from presidential candidates. This prevents small states from being overshadowed and ensures a fair distribution of campaign efforts.

Lastly, the Electoral College avoids the need for run-off elections in cases where no candidate receives a majority of the votes cast. This simplifies the presidential election process and reduces the need for additional elections. It provides a clear winner and prevents prolonged uncertainty and confusion.

While there are arguments against the Electoral College, such as potential voter disenfranchisement in states that have no chance of going to their preferred candidate, the data shows that voter turnout in presidential elections is still relatively high. Voters participate to express their political preference rather than with the belief that their vote will swing a national election.

In conclusion, the Electoral College system should be retained due to its practical advantages. It ensures certainty of outcome, trans-regional appeal for the president, engagement of swing states, balance for big states, and simplicity in election results. These reasons support the effectiveness and fairness of the Electoral College in choosing the president. I urge you to consider these points when determining your stance on this matter.

Sincerely,
