One advantage of limiting car usage is the reduction in greenhouse gas emissions and pollution. Cars are a major contributor to carbon emissions and air pollution, which have detrimental effects on the environment and human health. By reducing the number of cars on the road, we can significantly decrease these harmful emissions. For example, the German suburb of Vauban has seen a drastic reduction in greenhouse gas emissions as 70% of families do not own cars. Similarly, the city of Paris enforced a partial driving ban to clear the air of pollution, leading to a 60% reduction in congestion.

Another advantage of limiting car usage is the improvement in public health. By relying less on cars and encouraging alternative modes of transportation like walking, cycling, and public transportation, individuals can incorporate physical activity into their daily routines. This can lead to a decrease in sedentary lifestyles, obesity rates, and related health issues. In Vauban, residents have reported being happier and less stressed since giving up their cars, as they no longer have to deal with the frustrations of traffic congestion and parking.

Additionally, limiting car usage can lead to more sustainable and accessible communities. By designing neighborhoods and cities that prioritize pedestrians, cyclists, and public transportation, we can create urban spaces that are more compact, walkable, and connected. This not only improves the quality of life for residents but also makes it easier for people to access essential services, amenities, and employment opportunities without relying on cars. Vauban, for example, has placed stores within walking distance on a main street, transforming the traditional mall format.

