Dear Senator [Senator's Last Name],

I am writing to express my stance on the issue of the Electoral College and to argue in favor of keeping this system rather than changing to an election by popular vote for the president of the United States. After carefully considering the information provided in the texts mentioned, I believe that the Electoral College offers several practical advantages that warrant its retention.

First and foremost, the Electoral College ensures certainty of outcome. While disputes over the election outcome are possible, they are significantly less likely when compared to disputes over the popular vote. Since the winning candidate's share of the electoral vote typically exceeds their share of the popular vote, the electoral system provides a clear and decisive result. This certainty prevents prolonged periods of uncertainty and potential political instability that could arise from prolonged disputes over close popular votes.

Additionally, the Electoral College promotes the idea of everyone's president. By requiring a presidential candidate to have trans-regional appeal, the system ensures that no region has enough electoral votes to unilaterally elect a president. This prevents candidates with merely regional appeal from ignoring the interests of other regions and promotes a president who takes into account the diverse needs and perspectives of the entire nation.

Furthermore, the winner-take-all method of the Electoral College encourages candidates to focus their campaign efforts on swing states. This ensures that voters in these states receive heightened attention and information from the candidates, allowing them to make more informed decisions. These swing states tend to have the most thoughtful voters, who are more likely to pay close attention to the campaign and weigh the competing candidates' policies and proposals carefully.

In addition to promoting swing states, the Electoral College also restores balance for bigger states in the political sphere. Despite the malapportionment of the Senate, which disproportionately represents smaller states, the Electoral College provides larger states with more attention from candidates during campaigns. This proportional representation allows the concerns of larger states to receive greater consideration, ensuring a fairer distribution of resources and attention from future presidents.

Lastly, the Electoral College avoids the need for run-off elections. While it is possible for a candidate to win the presidency with a plurality of the popular vote, the Electoral College consistently produces a clear winner. This eliminates the need for lengthy and costly run-off elections, thereby streamlining the electoral process and avoiding potential confusion and political deadlock.

While some argue that the Electoral College discourages voters in states where they believe their vote will not affect the outcome, it is important to note that voter turnout remains high despite this perception. Voters participate to express their political preferences, rather than with the expectation that their single vote will sway a national election. Therefore, the impact of this argument is minimal and does not outweigh the practical advantages of the Electoral College.

In conclusion, the Electoral College has proven to be a valuable system that ensures certainty of outcome, promotes the idea of everyone's president, encourages focus on swing states, restores balance for big states, and avoids the complications of run-off elections. These practical advantages strongly support the retention of the Electoral College in choosing the president of the United States. I urge you to consider this perspective when evaluating any potential changes to our electoral system.

Thank you for your attention to this matter. I trust that you will carefully consider the points outlined in this letter and make a decision that is in the best interest of the American people.

Sincerely,

