Dear Senator [Last Name],

I am writing to express my support for keeping the Electoral College as the method of choosing the President of the United States. While there are arguments for changing to a popular vote system, I believe that the Electoral College is a fair and practical system that serves our nation well. I will outline the reasons for this position based on the information from various texts on the topic.

Firstly, the Electoral College ensures certainty of outcome. As highlighted by Judge Richard A. Posner in his defense of the Electoral College, disputes over the outcome of an Electoral College vote are less likely compared to the popular vote. This is due to the fact that the winning candidate's share of the Electoral College usually exceeds their share of the popular vote. The winner-take-all system in most states also contributes to a clear electoral-vote victory. This helps prevent prolonged disputes and ensures a more decisive outcome.

Secondly, the Electoral College promotes the representation of all regions of the country. With no single region having enough electoral votes to elect a president, candidates are incentivized to campaign in various states, aiming to appeal to a broader base of voters. This is an important aspect of the Electoral College, as it ensures that a president has trans-regional appeal and takes into account the interests of diverse regions. It prevents candidates with only regional appeal from becoming successful presidents and helps to avoid disenfranchisement of voters from other regions.

Thirdly, the Electoral College focuses campaign efforts on swing states. As mentioned by Judge Posner, the winner-take-all method of awarding electoral votes induces candidates to pay closer attention to toss-up states. This leads to more thoughtful and informed voters, as they know their votes hold significant weight in deciding the election. It encourages candidates to listen to the concerns and interests of swing state voters, ensuring a more comprehensive understanding of the electorate.

Fourthly, the Electoral College provides a balancing effect for large states. Due to the mal-apportionment of the Senate as outlined in the Constitution, larger states have less weight in the political balance. The Electoral College helps restore some of this balance by giving more attention to large states during campaigns. This ensures that presidential candidates do not solely focus on smaller states and their interests, but also take into account the needs and concerns of larger states.

Lastly, the Electoral College avoids the need for run-off elections. In situations where no candidate receives a majority of the popular votes, run-off elections can complicate the electoral process. The Electoral College, on the other hand, consistently produces a clear winner by requiring a majority of electoral votes. This eliminates the need for additional elections and provides a more straightforward decision-making process.

While it is true that some argue the Electoral College may discourage potential voters in states where their candidate has no chance of winning, the high turnout in presidential elections suggests that voters participate to express their political preferences rather than with the expectation of deciding the election. The Electoral College does not diminish the importance of voting but instead focuses on the collective voice of different regions in electing a president.

In conclusion, I believe that the Electoral College is a fair and effective system for choosing the President of the United States. It provides certainty of outcome, ensures representation of all regions, focuses campaign efforts on swing states, balances the influence of large states, and avoids the need for run-off elections. While there may be arguments for changing to a popular vote system, I believe that the merits of the Electoral College outweigh the potential drawbacks.

I kindly request that you consider these reasons and continue to support the Electoral College. It is a crucial part of our democratic process and plays a vital role in ensuring that the presidency represents the diverse interests of our nation.

Thank you for your attention to this matter. I trust that you will do what is best for our state and our country. Please do not hesitate to contact me if you have any additional questions or require further information.

Sincerely,

