"Dear Senator,

I am writing to express my support for the Electoral College and to argue against changing to an election by popular vote for the president of the United States. While I understand the criticisms of the Electoral College system, I believe that it has several important benefits that we should consider before making any changes.

First and foremost, the Electoral College provides certainty of outcome. In the event of a disputed election, it is less likely to occur with the Electoral College than with a popular vote. This is because the winning candidate's share of the Electoral College invariably exceeds their share of the popular vote. Additionally, the winner-take-all system in most states creates a landslide victory for the winning candidate if they have even a slight plurality in a state. While a tie in the nationwide electoral vote is possible, it is highly unlikely.

Another important advantage of the Electoral College is that it ensures that the president has trans-regional appeal. With no region having enough electoral votes to elect a president on its own, candidates must campaign across the country and appeal to voters in different regions. This prevents candidates with only regional appeal from winning the presidency, which is crucial for a successful presidency. It also ensures that residents of all regions feel represented and that their interests are taken into account by the president.

The winner-take-all method of awarding electoral votes also incentivizes candidates to campaign in swing states. This means that voters in these states have a greater say in deciding the election and are more likely to pay close attention to the campaign. These swing states also tend to have the most thoughtful voters, as they receive the most information and attention from the candidates. It is important that these informed voters have the power to decide the election.

Furthermore, the Electoral College restores some balance to the political weight that large states lose due to the mal-apportionment of the Senate. By giving more attention to large states during the campaign, the Electoral College ensures that their interests are not overlooked. It also avoids the problem of run-off elections, as a clear winner is invariably produced by the Electoral College even if no candidate receives a majority of the votes cast.

While there are arguments against the Electoral College, such as potential voter disengagement in non-competitive states, it is important to note that voters in presidential elections are people who want to express a political preference rather than people who think their vote may decide the election. Additionally, about half of the eligible American population voted in the last election, despite no voter's vote swinging a national election.

In conclusion, the Electoral College has several advantages that we should consider before making any changes to the current system. It provides certainty of outcome, ensures trans-regional appeal and representation, gives more power to swing states, balances political weight between large and small states, and avoids the need for run-off elections. While the system may not be perfect, it has proven to be effective in selecting our presidents. I urge you to consider these points before deciding on any changes to the Electoral College.

Thank you for your attention to this matter.

Sincerely,

