"Dear [State Senator],

I am writing to express my support for keeping the Electoral College system for electing the President of the United States. While there are arguments for switching to a popular vote system, I believe that the Electoral College has several practical advantages that would be lost if we were to make such a change.

One of the reasons to keep the Electoral College is the certainty of outcome. With the Electoral College, the winning candidate’s share of the electoral vote always exceeds their share of the popular vote. This means that there is less of a chance for disputes over the outcome of the election, as we saw in the 2000 election. Additionally, the winner-take-all method of awarding electoral votes allows even a slight plurality in a state to create a landslide electoral-vote victory. While a tie in the electoral vote is possible, it is highly unlikely. This certainty of outcome helps to maintain the integrity and stability of our election process.

Another reason to keep the Electoral College is that it ensures that the President has trans-regional appeal. No single region in the United States has enough electoral votes to elect a President, meaning that candidates cannot rely solely on the support of their own region. This encourages candidates to campaign across the entire country and have a broader appeal. This is important because a President with only regional support is unlikely to be successful in leading the entire nation. It also prevents some regions from feeling disenfranchised and ensures that the President is seen as the leader for all Americans, rather than just a particular region.

The Electoral College also benefits swing states and encourages candidates to pay attention to a diverse range of states. In elections, candidates focus their campaign efforts on swing states, where the outcome is uncertain. This makes voters in these states more likely to pay closer attention to the campaign and consider their choices carefully. These swing states tend to have more thoughtful voters who are better informed about the candidates' positions. This ensures that the most thoughtful voters have a greater impact on the election outcome, which is essential for a well-informed and representative democracy.

Additionally, the Electoral College helps to balance the influence of big states and small states. While the Senate already ensures that small states have a disproportionate say in national affairs, the Electoral College provides some weight to the political influence of large states as well. The winner-take-all method of allocating electoral votes means that large states receive more attention from candidates during campaigns. This helps to prevent an imbalance in the distribution of attention and resources and allows for a more representative electoral process.

Lastly, the Electoral College system avoids the need for run-off elections, which can complicate the process and create uncertainty. In cases where no candidate receives a majority of the votes cast, there is pressure for run-off elections. The Electoral College eliminates this problem by consistently producing a clear winner. This ensures a smooth and efficient electoral process without the need for additional rounds of voting.

While some argue that the Electoral College system may discourage voters in states where their preferred candidate has no chance of winning, it is worth noting that the majority of eligible Americans still participate in presidential elections. Voters are motivated to express their political preferences and are aware that a single vote may not decide an election. This demonstrates that the current system is effective in engaging voters and allowing them to have a voice in the election process.

In conclusion, I believe that keeping the Electoral College system for electing the President of the United States is the best option. The certainty of outcome, trans-regional appeal, focus on swing states, balance of influence between big and small states, and avoidance of run-off elections all contribute to a fair and representative electoral process. While there may be arguments for a popular vote system, the practical advantages of the Electoral College cannot be overlooked. I urge you to consider these points when discussing potential changes to our election system.

Sincerely,

