One advantage of limiting car usage is the reduction of greenhouse gas emissions. Cars are a major contributor to greenhouse gas emissions, which have a detrimental impact on the environment and contribute to climate change. In Europe, passenger cars alone are responsible for 12 percent of greenhouse gas emissions, and in some areas of the United States, this number can be as high as 50 percent (Passage 5). By limiting car usage, communities can significantly reduce their carbon footprint and work towards achieving environmental sustainability.

Another advantage of limiting car usage is the improvement of air quality. The use of cars, particularly those running on diesel fuel, contributes to high levels of pollutants in the air. For example, in Paris, the smog caused by car emissions led to a ban on driving, resulting in a 60 percent reduction in congestion and improved air quality (Passage 14). By reducing the number of cars on the road, communities can minimize air pollution and create a healthier and more liveable environment for residents.

