Dear Senator [Senator's Last Name],

I am writing to express my support for the retention of the Electoral College as the method of choosing the President of the United States. While some argue for a change to a popular vote system, I believe that the Electoral College has several practical reasons that make it a valuable and effective system.

Firstly, the Electoral College provides certainty of outcome. In the election of 2012, President Obama received 61.7% of the electoral vote, despite only receiving 51.3% of the popular vote. This demonstrates that the Electoral College method ensures that the winning candidate's share of the electoral votes exceeds their share of the popular vote. This reduces the likelihood of disputes over the outcome of the election, as witnessed in the 2000 election.

Secondly, the Electoral College ensures that the President is not solely a regional favorite, but instead requires trans-regional appeal. With no region having enough electoral votes to secure the presidency, candidates must campaign across the country. This promotes a broader understanding of the needs and concerns of various regions, preventing a candidate with only regional appeal from becoming president. It also ensures that every region feels represented and that the President will take their interests into account.

Furthermore, the emphasis on swing states, induced by the winner-take-all method, engages voters in those states to pay closer attention to the campaign and listen to competing candidates. These voters, being more thoughtful, are more likely to make informed decisions, thus ensuring that the most thoughtful voters are the ones deciding the outcome of the election.

In addition, the Electoral College balances the weight of large states against smaller states, mitigating the disproportionate influence established by the mal-apportionment of the Senate. Candidate attention is spread across the country, considering both large and small states. The example of Florida in the 2012 election illustrates how a close popular vote in a large state can have a significant impact on the outcome, whereas a similar margin in a small state would yield fewer electoral votes.

Lastly, the Electoral College avoids the need for run-off elections when no candidate receives a majority of the popular vote. It consistently produces a clear winner in the presidential election, eliminating the complications and potential delays associated with run-off elections.

Critics argue that the Electoral College may discourage potential voters in states where their preferred candidate has no hope of winning. However, the data from the 2012 elections shows that approximately half of the eligible American population still voted. Voters participate to express their political preferences, rather than with the expectation that a single vote may decide the election.

In conclusion, the Electoral College has practical reasons that demonstrate its value as a method of choosing the President. The certainty of outcome, trans-regional appeal, emphasis on swing states, balancing of large and small states, and avoidance of run-off elections all contribute to the effectiveness of the Electoral College. I urge you to consider these factors and maintain the Electoral College as the means of electing the President of the United States.

Thank you for your attention to this matter. I remain available to discuss this further and appreciate your continued service to our great state.

Sincerely,

