Similarly, in Paris, driving was banned due to intense smog and pollution. Motorists were fined for driving even-numbered or odd-numbered cars on designated days. The ban led to a 60 percent decrease in congestion and improved air quality. Diesel fuel was identified as a major cause of pollution, and exceptions were made for plug-in cars and hybrids. This shows that limiting car usage can have a direct impact on reducing air pollution and improving the environment.

Bogota, Colombia implemented a car-free day to promote alternative transportation and reduce smog. Millions of Colombians hiked, biked, skated, or took buses to work, leaving the streets devoid of traffic jams. The event was successful in raising awareness and generating enthusiasm among participants. The city of Bogota has invested in bike paths and sports centers, as well as implemented rush-hour restrictions to cut down on traffic. This shows that car-free initiatives can lead to improved infrastructure and a healthier environment.

In the United States, there has been a decrease in car ownership, driving, and the number of licenses issued. This shift in behavior suggests that America may have passed peak driving. The decrease in driving has positive implications for carbon emissions and the environment, as transportation is a major source of emissions. It also has the potential to shape the future of the car industry, with companies like Ford rebranding themselves as ""mobility"" companies with a broader product range. Factors such as the rise of the internet, telecommuting, and car-pooling apps have contributed to this shift in behavior.

