"Dear Senator,

I am writing to express my support for keeping the Electoral College as the method of selecting the President of the United States. While many argue for a change to election by popular vote, I believe that the Electoral College system has certain advantages that should not be overlooked.

One of the main arguments in favor of keeping the Electoral College is the certainty of outcome. As pointed out by Judge Richard A. Posner, the winning candidate's share of the Electoral College invariably exceeds their share of the popular vote. This means that a dispute over the outcome of an Electoral College vote is less likely than a dispute over the popular vote. This provides a level of stability and confidence in the election results.

Another advantage of the Electoral College is that it ensures that the President has trans-regional appeal. No single region in the country has enough electoral votes to elect a president. This means that candidates must appeal to a wide range of voters across different regions. This is important because a candidate with only regional appeal is unlikely to be a successful president. The Electoral College encourages candidates to campaign in different areas and address the concerns and interests of voters across the entire country.

Additionally, the winner-take-all method of awarding electoral votes encourages candidates to focus their campaign efforts on swing states. This ensures that voters in these states are more likely to pay close attention to the campaign and make informed decisions. This also prevents candidates from disregarding the interests of certain states, as they know that these states could be decisive in the election.

Furthermore, the Electoral College restores some balance to the political weight of large states. While the mal-apportionment of the Senate gives small states an advantage in terms of representation, the Electoral College gives larger states more attention from presidential candidates. This ensures that candidates cannot solely rely on winning the support of small states and must also address the concerns of larger, more populous states.

Lastly, the Electoral College avoids the problem of run-off elections when no candidate receives a majority of the votes cast. This reduces the complexity of the presidential election process and ensures that a clear winner emerges. It prevents prolonged periods of uncertainty and keeps the process streamlined.

While some argue that the Electoral College may discourage potential voters in states where their vote would not have an effect, it is important to note that voters in presidential elections are usually those who want to express a political preference rather than those who believe their vote could decide the outcome. The high turnout in recent presidential elections demonstrates that citizens are still motivated to vote, even with the Electoral College system in place.

In conclusion, the Electoral College system has several advantages that should be taken into account when considering a change to election by popular vote. It provides certainty of outcome, ensures trans-regional appeal, focuses campaign efforts on swing states, restores balance to large states, and avoids the complications of run-off elections. I urge you to consider these points and maintain the Electoral College as the method of selecting the President of the United States.

